definition.value: A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and L-serine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and L-phenylalanine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-methionine and L-alanine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-phenylalanine and glycine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and glycine residues.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the gamma-carboxy group of glutamic acid with the amino group of another glutamic acid.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the gamma-carboxy group of glutamic acid with the amino group of glutamine
A fatty amide obtained by the formal condensation of (11Z)-eicosaenoic acid with ethanolamine.
A dipeptide formed from L-alanyl and L-leucine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-arginine and L-phenylalanine residues. It exhibits vasorelaxant activity.
A  lysophosphatidylcholine P-16:0 in which the alk-1-enyl group is hexadec-1-en-1-yl.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 18:0 in which the acyl substituent is located at position 1 and is specified as stearoyl.
A dipeptide formed from glycine and L-tryptophan residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-histidine and L-alanine residues.
A 2-monoglyceride where the acyl group is (9Z)-octadecenoyl.
A phosphatidylcholine 32:1 in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 are hexadecanoyl and (9Z)-hexadec-9-enoyl respectively.
A dipeptide formed from L-histidine and L-valine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-isoleucine and glycine residues.
A nucleoside analogue that is allopurinol with a beta-D-ribofuranosyl moiety at the 1-position.

An S-hydrocarbyl-L-cysteine that is L-cysteine in which the  hydrogen attached to the sulphur is replaced by a prop-2-enyl group. It commonly occurs in garlic and has been found to exhibit antineoplastic activity.
A cholesterol ester in which the acyl group contains 22 carbons in total and 6 double bonds.
A dipeptide formed from L-isoleucine and L-valine residues.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 22:5 in which the acyl group at position 1 is (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z)-docosapentaenoyl and the hydroxy group at position 2 is unsubstituted.
A member of the class of formamides  having a N-methyl substituent.
A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and L-glutamic acid residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and glycine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-lysine and L-leucine residues.
A  N-acetyl-L-amino acid that is the N-acetyl derivative of L-tryptophan.
A 3-oxo Delta(4)-steroid that is estr-4-en-3-one substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 17.
A  phosphatidylcholine 36:3 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and linoleoyl respectively.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-alanine residues.

A methoxynaphthalene that is 2-methoxynaphthalene substituted by a carboxy ethyl group at position 6. Naproxen is a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug commonly used for the reduction of pain, fever, inflammation  and stiffness caused by conditions such as osteoarthritis, kidney stones, rheumatoid arthritis, psoriatic arthritis, gout, ankylosing spondylitis, menstrual cramps, tendinitis, bursitis, and for the treatment of primary dysmenorrhea. It works by inhibiting both the COX-1 and COX-2 enzymes.
A dipeptide composed of L-proline and L-hydroxyproline residues. It is a biomarker for bone collagen degradation.
A dipeptide formed from L-serine and L-leucine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-threonine and L-phenylalanine residues.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate(2-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 1-arachidonoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate.
A phosphatidylcholine 38:4 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as stearoyl and arachidonoyl respectively.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and L-leucine residues.
A phosphatidylcholine 36:1 in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are stearoyl and oleoyl respectively.
An organofluorine compound and antineoplastic agent, used as its mesylate salt in treatment of metastatic melanoma.
A phosphatidylcholine 30:0 in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are myristoyl (tetradecanoyl) and palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl) respectively.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1-acyl group is specified as oleoyl.
A 1-monoglyceride where the acyl group is oleoyl.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where oleoyl and linoleoyl are the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
A 1-monoglyceride that has octadecadienoyl (linoleoyl) as the acyl group.

A dihydropyridine that is 1,4-dihydropyridine which is substituted by methyl groups at positions 2 and 6, a (2-methoxyethoxy)carbonyl group at position 3, a m-nitrophenyl group at position 4, and an isopropoxycarbonyl group at position 5. An L-type calcium channel blocker, it acts particularly on cerebral circulation, and is used both orally and intravenously for the prevention and treatment of subarachnoid hemorrhage from ruptured intracranial aneurysm.
The R-enantiomer of 2-hydroxyhexadecanoate.
The S-enantiomer of 2-hydroxypalmitate.

A pyridopyrimidine that is used (as its dimethyl sulfoxide addition compound) for the treatment of patients with unresectable or metastatic melanoma with BRAF V600E or V600K mutations, and who have not received prior BRAF inhibitor treatment.
